# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dear-imgui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] A **framebuffer** (**frame buffer**, or sometimes **framestore**) is a portion of random-access memory (RAM) containing a bitmap that drives a video display.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] It is a memory buffer containing data representing all the pixels in a complete video frame.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Modern video cards contain framebuffer circuitry in their cores.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] This circuitry helps convert an in-memory bitmap into a video signal that can be displayed on a computer monitor.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] In computing, a **screen buffer** is a part of computer memory used by a computer application for the representation of the content to be shown on the computer display.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The screen buffer may also be called the **video buffer**, the **regeneration buffer**, or **regen buffer** for short.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The phrase "screen buffer” refers to a logical function, while *video memory* refers to a hardware storage location.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] In particular, the screen buffer may be placed in the main RAM, the video memory, or some other hardware location.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] To reduce latency and avoid screen tearing, multiple frames can be buffered, and this technique is called multiple buffering.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] When this is so, at any time, only one frame would be visible, and the others would not be.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The currently invisible frames are located in the **off-screen buffer**.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The information in the buffer typically consists of color values for every pixel to be shown on the display.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Color values are commonly stored in 1-bit binary (monochrome), 4-bit palettized, 8-bit palettized, 16-bit high color and 24-bit true color formats.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] An additional alpha channel is sometimes used to retain information about pixel transparency.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The total amount of memory required for the framebuffer depends on the resolution of the output signal, and on the color depth or palette size.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Computer researchers had long discussed the theoretical advantages of a framebuffer but were unable to produce a machine with sufficient memory at an economically practicable cost.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] In 1947, the Manchester Baby computer used a Williams tube, later the Williams-Kilburn tube, to store 1024 bits on a cathode-ray tube (CRT) memory and displayed on a second CRT.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Other research labs were exploring these techniques with MIT Lincoln Laboratory achieving a 4096 display in 1950.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] A color-scanned display was implemented in the late 1960s, called the Brookhaven RAster Display (BRAD), which used a drum memory and a television monitor.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Michael Noll of Bell Telephone Laboratories, Inc. implemented a scanned display with a frame buffer, using magnetic-core memory.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] A year or so later, the Bell Labs system was expanded to display an image with a color depth of three bits on a standard color TV monitor.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The vector graphics used in the computer had to be converted for the scanned graphics of a TV display.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] This led to the development of the SuperPaint system by Richard Shoup at Xerox PARC in 1972.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Shoup was able to use the SuperPaint framebuffer to create an early digital video-capture system.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] By synchronizing the output signal to the input signal, Shoup was able to overwrite each pixel of data as it shifted in.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Shoup also experimented with modifying the output signal using color tables.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] These color tables allowed the SuperPaint system to produce a wide variety of colors outside the range of the limited 8-bit data it contained.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] This scheme would later become commonplace in computer framebuffers.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] In 1974, Evans & Sutherland released the first commercial framebuffer, the Picture System, costing about $15,000.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] It was capable of producing resolutions of up to 512 by 512 pixels in 8-bit grayscale, and became a boon for graphics researchers who did not have the resources to build their own framebuffer.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The New York Institute of Technology would later create the first 24-bit color system using three of the Evans & Sutherland framebuffers.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Each framebuffer was connected to an RGB color output (one for red, one for green and one for blue), with a Digital Equipment Corporation PDP 11/04 minicomputer controlling the three devices as one.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] In 1975, the UK company Quantel produced the first commercial full-color broadcast framebuffer, the Quantel DFS 3000.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] It was first used in TV coverage of the 1976 Montreal Olympics to generate a picture-in-picture inset of the Olympic flaming torch while the rest of the picture featured the runner entering the stadium.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The rapid improvement of integrated-circuit technology made it possible for many of the home computers of the late 1970s to contain low-color-depth framebuffers.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Today, nearly all computers with graphical capabilities utilize a framebuffer for generating the video signal.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Amiga computers, created in the 1980s, featured special design attention to graphics performance and included a unique Hold-And-Modify framebuffer capable of displaying 4096 colors.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Framebuffers also became popular in high-end workstations and arcade system boards throughout the 1980s.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] SGI, Sun Microsystems, HP, DEC and IBM all released framebuffers for their workstation computers in this period.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] These framebuffers were usually of a much higher quality than could be found in most home computers, and were regularly used in television, printing, computer modeling and 3D graphics.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Framebuffers were also used by Sega for its high-end arcade boards, which were also of a higher quality than on home computers.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Framebuffers used in personal and home computing often had sets of defined *modes* under which the framebuffer can operate.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] These modes reconfigure the hardware to output different resolutions, color depths, memory layouts and refresh rate timings.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] In the world of Unix machines and operating systems, such conveniences were usually eschewed in favor of directly manipulating the hardware settings.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] This manipulation was far more flexible in that any resolution, color depth and refresh rate was attainable – limited only by the memory available to the framebuffer.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] An unfortunate side-effect of this method was that the display device could be driven beyond its capabilities.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] In some cases, this resulted in hardware damage to the display.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] More commonly, it simply produced garbled and unusable output.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Modern CRT monitors fix this problem through the introduction of protection circuitry.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] When the display mode is changed, the monitor attempts to obtain a signal lock on the new refresh frequency.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] If the monitor is unable to obtain a signal lock or if the signal is outside the range of its design limitations, the monitor will ignore the framebuffer signal and possibly present the user with an error message.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] LCD monitors tend to contain similar protection circuitry, but for different reasons.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Since the LCD must digitally sample the display signal (thereby emulating an electron beam), any signal that is out of range cannot be physically displayed on the monitor.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Framebuffers have traditionally supported a wide variety of color modes.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Due to the expense of memory, most early framebuffers used 1-bit (2 colors per pixel), 2-bit (4 colors), 4-bit (16 colors) or 8-bit (256 colors) color depths.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The problem with such small color depths is that a full range of colors cannot be produced.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The solution to this problem was indexed color, which adds a lookup table to the framebuffer.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Each color stored in framebuffer memory acts as a color index.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The lookup table serves as a palette with a limited number of different colors, while the rest is used as an index table.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] In some designs, it was also possible to write data to the lookup table (or switch between existing palettes) on the fly, allowing dividing the picture into horizontal bars with their own palette and thus rendering an image that had a far wider palette.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] For example, viewing an outdoor shot photograph, the picture could be divided into four bars: the top one with emphasis on sky tones, the next with foliage tones, the next with skin and clothing tones, and the bottom one with ground colors.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] This required each palette to have overlapping colors, but, carefully done, allowed great flexibility.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] While framebuffers are commonly accessed via a memory mapping directly to the CPU memory space, this is not the only method by which they may be accessed.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Framebuffers have varied widely in the methods used to access memory.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The framebuffer organization may be packed pixel or planar.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The framebuffer may be all points addressable or have restrictions on how it can be updated.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Video cards always have a certain amount of RAM.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] A small portion of this RAM is where the bitmap of image data is "buffered" for display.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The term *frame buffer* is thus often used interchangeably when referring to this RAM.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The CPU sends image updates to the video card.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The video processor on the card forms a picture of the screen image and stores it in the frame buffer as a large bitmap in RAM.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The bitmap in RAM is used by the card to continually refresh the screen image.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Many systems attempt to emulate the function of a framebuffer device, often for reasons of compatibility.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The two most common virtual framebuffers are the Linux framebuffer device (fbdev) and the X Virtual Framebuffer (Xvfb).
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Xvfb was added to the X Window System distribution to provide a method for running X without a graphical framebuffer.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The Linux framebuffer device was developed to abstract the physical method for accessing the underlying framebuffer into a guaranteed memory map that is easy for programs to access.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] This increases portability, as programs are not required to deal with systems that have disjointed memory maps or require bank switching.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] A frame buffer may be designed with enough memory to store two frames' worth of video data.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] In a technique known generally as double buffering or more specifically as page flipping, the framebuffer uses half of its memory to display the current frame.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] While that memory is being displayed, the other half of the memory is filled with data for the next frame.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Once the secondary buffer is filled, the framebuffer is instructed to display the secondary buffer instead.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The primary buffer becomes the secondary buffer, and the secondary buffer becomes the primary.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] This switch is often done after the vertical blanking interval to avoid screen tearing where half the old frame and half the new frame is shown together.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Page flipping has become a standard technique used by PC game programmers.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] As the demand for better graphics increased, hardware manufacturers created a way to decrease the amount of CPU time required to fill the framebuffer.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] This is commonly called *graphics acceleration*.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Common graphics drawing commands (many of them geometric) are sent to the graphics accelerator in their raw form.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The accelerator then rasterizes the results of the command to the framebuffer.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] This method frees the CPU to do other work.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Early accelerators focused on improving the performance of 2D GUI systems.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] While retaining these 2D capabilities, most modern accelerators focus on producing 3D imagery in real time.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] A common design uses a graphics library such as OpenGL or Direct3D, which interfaces with the graphics driver to translate received commands to instructions for the accelerator's graphics processing unit (GPU).
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The GPU uses those instructions to compute the rasterized results and the results are bit blitted to the framebuffer.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The framebuffer's signal is then produced in combination with built-in video overlay devices (usually used to produce the mouse cursor without modifying the framebuffer's data) and any final special effects that are produced by modifying the output signal.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] An example of such final special effects was the spatial anti-aliasing technique used by the 3dfx Voodoo cards.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] These cards add a slight blur to the output signal that makes aliasing of the rasterized graphics much less obvious.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] At one time there were many manufacturers of graphics accelerators, including: 3dfx Interactive; ATI; Hercules; Trident; Nvidia; Radius; S3 Graphics; SiS and Silicon Graphics.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] As of 2015 the market for graphics accelerators for x86-based systems is dominated by Nvidia (acquired 3dfx in 2002), AMD (who acquired ATI in 2006), and Intel.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] With a framebuffer, the electron beam (if the display technology uses one) is commanded to perform a raster scan, the way a television renders a broadcast signal.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The color information for each point thus displayed on the screen is pulled directly from the framebuffer during the scan, creating a set of discrete picture elements, i.e., pixels.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Framebuffers differ significantly from the vector displays that were common prior to the advent of raster graphics (and, consequently, to the concept of a framebuffer).
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] With a vector display, only the vertices of the graphics primitives are stored.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The electron beam of the output display is then commanded to move from vertex to vertex, tracing a line across the area between these points.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] Likewise, framebuffers differ from the technology used in early text mode displays, where a buffer holds codes for characters, not individual pixels.
[src:dear-imgui/framebuffer] The video display device performs the same raster scan as with a framebuffer but generates the pixels of each character in the buffer as it directs the beam.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] without the use of extensive indirection – thus***immediate***– to retained resources.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] It does not preclude the use of double-buffering.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Retained mode is an alternative approach.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusive in practice.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] In immediate mode, the scene (complete object model of the rendering primitives) is retained in the memory space of the client, instead of the graphics library.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This implies that in an immediate mode application, the lists of graphical objects to be rendered are kept by the client and are not saved by the graphics library API.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] The application must re-issue all drawing commands required to describe the entire scene each time a new frame is required, regardless of actual changes.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This method provides on the one hand a maximum of control and flexibility to the application program, but on the other hand it also generates continuous work load on the CPU.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Examples of immediate mode rendering systems include Direct2D, OpenGL and Quartz.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] There are some immediate mode GUIs that are particularly suitable when used in conjunction with immediate mode rendering systems.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Primitive vertex attribute data may be inserted frame by frame into a command buffer by a rendering API.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This involves significant bandwidth and processor time (especially if the graphics processing unit is on a separate bus), but may be advantageous for data generated dynamically by the CPU.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] It is less common since the advent of increasingly versatile shaders, with which a graphics processing unit may generate increasingly complex effects without the need for CPU intervention.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Graphical user interfaces traditionally use retained mode-style API design, but immediate mode GUIs instead use an immediate mode-style API design, in which user code directly specifies the GUI elements to draw in the user input loop.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] For example, rather than having a CreateButton() function that a user would call once to instantiate a button, an immediate-mode GUI API may have a DoButton() function which should be called whenever the button should be on screen.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] The technique was developed by Casey Muratori in 2002.
[src:dear-imgui/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Prominent implementations include Omar Cornut's Dear ImGui in C++, Nic Barker's Clay in C and Micha Mettke's Nuklear in C.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] (SGI) began developing OpenGL in 1991 and released it on June 30, 1992.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] It is used for a variety of applications, including computer-aided design (CAD), video games, scientific visualization, virtual reality, and flight simulation.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Since 2006, OpenGL has been managed by the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The OpenGL specification describes an abstract application programming interface (API) for drawing 2D and 3D graphics.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] It is designed to be implemented mostly or entirely using hardware acceleration such as a GPU, although it is possible for the API to be implemented entirely in software running on a CPU.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The API is defined as a set of functions which may be called by the client program, alongside a set of named integer constants (for example, the constant GL_TEXTURE_2D, which corresponds to the decimal number 3553).
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Although the function definitions are superficially similar to those of the programming language C, they are language-independent.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] As such, OpenGL has many language bindings, some of the most noteworthy being the JavaScript binding WebGL (API, based on OpenGL ES 2.0, for 3D rendering from within a web browser); the C bindings WGL, GLX and CGL; the C binding provided by iOS; and the Java and C bindings provided by Android.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] In addition to being language-independent, OpenGL is also cross-platform.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The specification says nothing on the subject of obtaining and managing an OpenGL context, leaving this as a detail of the underlying windowing system.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] For the same reason, OpenGL is purely concerned with rendering, providing no APIs related to input, audio, or windowing.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] New versions of the OpenGL specifications are released by the Khronos Group, each of which extends the API to support various new features.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The details of each version are decided by consensus between the Group's members, including graphics card manufacturers, operating system designers, and general technology companies such as Mozilla and Google.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] In addition to the features required by the core API, graphics processing unit (GPU) vendors may provide additional functionality in the form of *extensions*.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Extensions may introduce new functions and new constants, and may relax or remove restrictions on existing OpenGL functions.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Vendors can use extensions to expose custom APIs without needing support from other vendors or the Khronos Group as a whole, which greatly increases the flexibility of OpenGL.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] All extensions are collected in, and defined by, the OpenGL Registry.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The features introduced by each new version of OpenGL are typically formed from the combined features of several widely implemented extensions, especially extensions of type ARB or EXT.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL is no longer in active development; whereas between 2001 and 2014, OpenGL specification was updated mostly on a yearly basis, with two releases (3.1 and 3.2) taking place in 2009 and three (3.3, 4.0 and 4.1) in 2010.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The latest OpenGL specification 4.6 was released in 2017 after a three-year break, and was limited to inclusion of eleven existing ARB and EXT extensions into the core profile.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Active development of OpenGL was dropped in favor of the Vulkan API, released in 2016, and codenamed glNext during initial development.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] In 2017, Khronos Group announced that OpenGL ES would not have new versions and has since concentrated on development of Vulkan and other technologies.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] As a result, certain capabilities offered by modern GPUs, e.g. ray tracing, are not supported by the OpenGL standard.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] However, support for newer features might be provided through the vendor-specific OpenGL extensions.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The OpenGL Architecture Review Board released a series of manuals along with the specification which have been updated to track changes in the API.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL Programming for the X Window System.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Includes a poster-sized fold-out diagram showing the structure of an idealised OpenGL implementation.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL Programming for Windows 95 and Windows NT.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] A book about interfacing OpenGL with Microsoft Windows.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL's documentation is also accessible via its official webpage.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The earliest versions of OpenGL were released with a companion library called the OpenGL Utility Library (GLU).
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] It provided simple, useful features which were unlikely to be supported in contemporary hardware, such as tessellating, and generating mipmaps and primitive shapes.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The GLU specification was last updated in 1998 and depends on OpenGL features which are now deprecated.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Given that creating an OpenGL context is quite a complex process, and given that it varies between operating systems, automatic OpenGL context creation has become a common feature of several game-development and user-interface libraries, including SDL, Allegro, SFML, FLTK, and Qt.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] A few libraries have been designed solely to produce an OpenGL-capable window.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The first such library was OpenGL Utility Toolkit (GLUT), later superseded by freeglut.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Given the high workload involved in identifying and loading OpenGL extensions, a few libraries have been designed which load all available extensions and functions automatically.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Examples include OpenGL Easy Extension library (GLEE), OpenGL Extension Wrangler Library (GLEW) and glbinding.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Extensions are also loaded automatically by most language bindings, such as Java OpenGL, PyOpenGL and WebGL.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Mesa 3D is an open-source implementation of OpenGL.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] It can do pure software rendering, and it may also use hardware acceleration on BSD, Linux, and other platforms by taking advantage of the Direct Rendering Infrastructure.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] As of version 20.0, it implements version 4.6 of the OpenGL standard.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] In the 1980s, developing software that could function with a wide range of graphics hardware was a challenge without a cross-platform library.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Software developers wrote custom interfaces and drivers for each piece of hardware.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] This was expensive and resulted in multiplication of effort.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] By the early 1990s, Silicon Graphics (SGI) was a leader in 3D graphics for workstations.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Their IRIS GL API became the industry standard, as IRIS GL was considered easier to use, and it supported immediate mode rendering, therefore being faster than competitors like PHIGS.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] SGI's competitors (including Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and IBM) were also able to bring to market 3D hardware supported by extensions made to the PHIGS standard, which pressured SGI to open source a version of IRIS GL as a public standard called **OpenGL**.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] However, SGI had many customers for whom the change from IRIS GL to OpenGL would demand significant investment.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Moreover, IRIS GL had API functions that were irrelevant to 3D graphics.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] For example, it included a windowing, keyboard and mouse API, in part because it was developed before the X Window System and Sun's NeWS.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] IRIS GL libraries were heavily tied into SGI's proprietary graphics hardware and could not be open sourced as-is due to hardware patents and trade secrets.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] These factors required SGI to continue to support the advanced and proprietary Iris Inventor and Iris Performer programming APIs while market support for OpenGL matured.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] One of the restrictions of IRIS GL was that it only provided access to features supported by the underlying hardware.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] If the graphics hardware did not support a feature natively, then the application could not use it.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL overcame this problem by providing software implementations of features unsupported by hardware, allowing applications to use advanced graphics on relatively low-powered systems.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL standardized access to hardware, pushed the development responsibility of hardware interface programs (device drivers) to hardware manufacturers, and delegated windowing functions to the underlying operating system.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] With so many different kinds of graphics hardware, getting them all to speak the same language in this way had a remarkable impact by giving software developers a higher-level platform for 3D-software development.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] In 1992, SGI led the creation of the OpenGL Architecture Review Board (OpenGL ARB), the group of companies that would maintain and expand the OpenGL specification in the future.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Two years later, they also played with the idea of releasing something called "OpenGL++" which included elements such as a scene-graph API (presumably based on their Performer technology).
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The specification was circulated among a few interested parties – but never turned into a product.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Released in 1996, Microsoft's Direct3D eventually became the main competitor of OpenGL.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Over 50 game developers signed an open letter to Microsoft, released on June 12, 1997, calling on the company to actively support OpenGL.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] On December 17, 1997, Microsoft and SGI initiated the Fahrenheit project, which was a joint effort with the goal of unifying the OpenGL and Direct3D interfaces (and adding a scene-graph API too).
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] In 1998, Hewlett-Packard joined the project.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] It initially showed some promise of bringing order to the world of interactive 3D computer graphics APIs, but on account of financial constraints at SGI, strategic reasons at Microsoft, and a general lack of industry support, it was abandoned in 1999.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] In July 2006, the OpenGL Architecture Review Board voted to transfer control of the OpenGL API standard to the Khronos Group.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL was the standard for many CAD software (such as Blender) and games in the 1990s and 2000s, and faces wide support across virtually all hardware vendors.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Despite the emergence of newer graphics APIs like its successor Vulkan or Metal, OpenGL continues to be a widely used standard.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] This continued relevance is supported by several factors: ongoing development with new extensions and driver optimizations, its cross-platform compatibility, and the availability of compatibility layers like ANGLE and Zink.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] These layers allow OpenGL to run efficiently on top of Vulkan and Metal, offering a pathway for continued use or gradual transitions for developers.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] However, the graphics API landscape has been shifting, where some companies are moving away from OpenGL.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] In June 2018, Apple deprecated OpenGL APIs on all of their platforms (iOS, macOS and tvOS), encouraging developers to use their proprietary Metal API, which was introduced in 2014.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Game developers have also begun to adopt newer APIs. id Software, who has been using OpenGL in their games since the late 1990s in games such as GLQuake or some games of the Doom franchise, transitioned away to its successor Vulkan in its id Tech 7 engine in 2016.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] They first supported Vulkan in an update for their id Tech 6 engine.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The company's first licensed use of OpenGL was in its Quake II engine, also known as id Tech 2.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] In March 2023, Valve removed OpenGL support from Dota 2 in favor of Vulkan.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Atypical Games, with support from Samsung, updated their game engine to use Vulkan, rather than OpenGL, across all non-Apple platforms.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The Khronos Group, the consortium responsible for OpenGL's development, has stopped updating OpenGL, with the last release made in 2017.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] It has not received a number of modern graphics technologies, such as hardware accelerated Ray Tracing, on-GPU video decoding, and advanced anti-aliasing algorithms like Nvidia DLSS and AMD FSR.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Another modern feature, Mesh Shaders, was initially only supported through an Nvidia exclusive extension, however in 2025, a cross-vendor OpenGL Mesh Shader extension was released.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Google's Fuchsia OS, while using Vulkan natively and requiring a Vulkan-conformant GPU, still intends to support OpenGL on top of Vulkan via the ANGLE translation layer.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The first version of OpenGL, version 1.0, was released on June 30, 1992, by Mark Segal and Kurt Akeley.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Since then, OpenGL has occasionally been extended by releasing a new version of the specification.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Such releases define a baseline set of features which all conforming graphics cards must support, and against which new extensions can more easily be written.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Each new version of OpenGL tends to incorporate several extensions which have widespread support among graphics-card vendors, although the details of those extensions may be changed.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL 2.0 was originally conceived by 3Dlabs to address concerns that OpenGL was stagnating and lacked a strong direction.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] 3Dlabs proposed a number of major additions to the standard.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Most of these were, at the time, rejected by the ARB or otherwise never came to fruition in the form that 3Dlabs proposed.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] However, their proposal for a C-style shading language was eventually completed, resulting in the current formulation of the OpenGL Shading Language (GLSL or GLslang).
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Like the assembly-like shading languages it was replacing, it allowed replacing the fixed-function vertex and fragment pipe with shaders, though this time written in a C-like high-level language.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The design of GLSL was notable for making relatively few concessions to the limits of the hardware then available.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] This harked back to the earlier tradition of OpenGL setting an ambitious, forward-looking target for 3D accelerators rather than merely tracking the state of currently available hardware.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The final OpenGL 2.0 specification includes support for GLSL 1.10.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL 2.1 adds support for Pixel Buffer Objects, sRGB textures and GLSL 1.20.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Before the release of OpenGL 3.0, the new revision had the codename Longs Peak.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] At the time of its original announcement, Longs Peak was presented as the first major API revision in OpenGL's lifetime.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] It consisted of an overhaul to the way that OpenGL works, calling for fundamental changes to the API.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The draft introduced a change to object management.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The GL 2.1 object model was built upon the state-based design of OpenGL.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] That is, to modify an object or to use it, one needs to bind the object to the state system, then make modifications to the state or perform function calls that use the bound object.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Because of OpenGL's use of a state system, objects must be mutable.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] That is, the basic structure of an object can change at any time, even if the rendering pipeline is asynchronously using that object.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] A texture object can be redefined from 2D to 3D.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] This requires any OpenGL implementations to add a degree of complexity to internal object management.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Under the Longs Peak API, object creation would become atomic, using templates to define the properties of an object which would be created with one function call.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The object could then be used immediately across multiple threads.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Objects would also be immutable; however, they could have their contents changed and updated.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] For example, a texture could change its image, but its size and format could not be changed.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] To support backwards compatibility, the old state based API would still be available, but no new functionality would be exposed via the old API in later versions of OpenGL.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] This would have allowed legacy code bases, such as the majority of CAD products, to continue to run while other software could be written against or ported to the new API.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Longs Peak was initially due to be finalized in September 2007 under the name OpenGL 3.0, but the Khronos Group announced on October 30 that it had run into several issues that it wished to address before releasing the specification.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] As a result, the spec was delayed, and the Khronos Group went into a media blackout until the release of the final OpenGL 3.0 spec.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The final specification proved far less revolutionary than the Longs Peak proposal.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Instead of removing all immediate mode and fixed functionality (non-shader mode), the spec included them as deprecated features.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The proposed object model was not included, and no plans have been announced to include it in any future revisions.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] As a result, the API remained largely the same with a few existing extensions being promoted to core functionality.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Among some developer groups this decision caused something of an uproar, with many developers professing that they would switch to DirectX in protest.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Most complaints revolved around the lack of communication by Khronos to the development community and multiple features being discarded that were viewed favorably by many.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Other frustrations included the requirement of DirectX 10 level hardware to use OpenGL 3.0 and the absence of geometry shaders and instanced rendering as core features.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Other sources reported that the community reaction was not quite as severe as originally presented, with many vendors showing support for the update.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 introduced a deprecation mechanism to simplify future revisions of the API.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Certain features, marked as deprecated, could be completely disabled by requesting a *forward-compatible context* from the windowing system.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 features could still be accessed alongside these deprecated features, however, by requesting a *full context*.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 8 Series and newer, ATI Radeon HD 2000 series and newer, Intel HD Graphics in Intel Sandy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL 3.1 fully removed all of the features which were deprecated in version 3.0, with the exception of wide lines.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] From this version onwards, it's not possible to access new features using a *full context*, or to access deprecated features using a *forward-compatible context*.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] An exception to the former rule is made if the implementation supports the ARB_compatibility extension, but this is not guaranteed.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Hardware support: Mesa supports ARM Panfrost with Version 21.0.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 further built on the deprecation mechanisms introduced by OpenGL 3.0, by dividing the specification into a *core profile* and *compatibility profile*.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Compatibility contexts include the previously removed fixed-function APIs, equivalent to the ARB_compatibility extension released alongside OpenGL 3.1, while core contexts do not.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 also included an upgrade to GLSL version 1.50.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL 3.3 includes minor additions, with the goal of retaining as much functionality as possible from OpenGL 4.0, while keeping support for older hardware.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Additions include new blending functions, Sampler Objects and new texture and vertex formats.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Support is also added for GLSL version 3.30, major and minor versions now match with OpenGL.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] OpenGL 4.0 was released alongside version 3.3.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] It was designed for hardware able to support Direct3D 11.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] As in OpenGL 3.0, this version of OpenGL contains a high number of fairly inconsequential extensions, designed to thoroughly expose the abilities of Direct3D 11-class hardware, such as tessellation.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Ivy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge and newer).
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Additionally, this is the last core profile supported by Apple macOS.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), and Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge without stencil texturing, Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] VIRGL Emulation for virtual machines supports 4.3+ with Mesa 20.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1, and Tegra X1.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 7000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel Skylake and newer, Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Apple deprecated OpenGL in iOS 12 and macOS 10.14 Mojave in favor of Metal, but it is still available as of macOS 15 Sequoia (including on Apple silicon devices).
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The latest version supported for OpenGL is 4.1 from 2011.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] A proprietary library from Molten – authors of MoltenVK – called MoltenGL, can translate OpenGL calls to Metal.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] There are several projects that attempt to implement OpenGL on top of Vulkan.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The Vulkan backend for Google's ANGLE achieved OpenGL ES 3.1 conformance in July 2020.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The Mesa3D project also includes such a driver, called *Zink*.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Microsoft's Windows 11 on Arm added support for OpenGL 3.3 via GLon12, an open source OpenGL implementation on top DirectX 12 via Mesa Gallium.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] Vulkan, formerly named the "Next Generation OpenGL Initiative" (glNext), is a ground-up redesign effort to unify OpenGL and OpenGL ES into one common API that will not be backwards compatible with existing OpenGL versions.
[src:dear-imgui/opengl] The initial version of Vulkan API was released on February 16, 2016.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:dear-imgui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
[src:dear-imgui/retained-mode] Immediate mode is an alternative approach.
[src:dear-imgui/retained-mode] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusionary in practice.
[src:dear-imgui/retained-mode] In retained mode the client calls do not directly cause actual rendering, but instead update an abstract internal model (typically a list of objects) which is maintained within the library's data space.
[src:dear-imgui/retained-mode] This allows the library to optimize when actual rendering takes place along with the processing of related objects.
[src:dear-imgui/retained-mode] Example of coexistence with immediate mode in the same library is OpenGL.
[src:dear-imgui/retained-mode] OpenGL has immediate mode functions that can use previously defined server side objects (textures, vertex buffers and index buffers, shaders, etc.) without resending unchanged data.
[src:dear-imgui/retained-mode] Examples of retained mode rendering systems include Windows Presentation Foundation, SceneKit on macOS, and PHIGS.
